Dear followers-
Our little superhero has tested positive for Covid. He’s been home from school since Wednesday due to a COVID case in his classroom and developed symptoms yesterday. Thankfully, everyone in our home has tested negative and we are doing our best to stay safe, especially my grandmother who was recently admitted into the hospital and has returned home. At this time, Noah’s symptoms and fevers are mild and he’s in good spirits. Doctors have informed me that due to his heart and lung disease, we have to go to the ER should anything change.  I’m hoping tonight he sleeps better than yesterday. I will try my best to keep you guys updated but in the meantime need all the prayers possible 🙏🏽 Thank you in advance ❤️

COVID - Day 3 and Mr Noah is using his superpowers to fight this virus the best way he can. I remember not too long ago, just the thought of Noah having COVID would give me anxiety but surprisingly, when I found out he had it, I was calm and confident that he would get through it despite his heart and lung disease. I wasn’t sure how bad it would get but I trusted that the foods that I prepared for him on a daily basis would prepare him for this day. I also keep my faith in God and all that he has done and continues to do for Noah. He’s doing well despite the stuffy and runny nose, coughing from time to time and fevers. The coughs don’t sound as dry anymore which is a good indication that he’s getting better. He is not as playful as he usually is but still continues to sing his favorite songs. I thank you for all for the well wishes and prayers. We are still not out of the woods yet but for now, he’s doing good! 🙏🏽💛💙

Woke up this morning so happy to see the number of signatures we already have in support of the Choosing Noah Bill. I ask that you sign and share to help us bring awareness to something that is happening here in United States and all over the world. Please help me change that by signing. For the link please click the link in our bio 💛💙 Btw, World Down Syndrome Day is March 21, let’s get as many signatures and get this bill passed by this date! 🙏🏽

It is unclear the exact number of babies prenatally diagnosed with Down Syndrome that are aborted in the United States each year, but we continue to see most often in print a statistic of 90-92%. While that certainly draws attention to the horrifying reality that the majority of children prenatally diagnosed with Down Syndrome are aborted, a change can definitely happen nationally by passing the Choosing Noah Bill. This bill will require medical staff to communicate a prenatal diagnosis in a neutral way, without accompanying it with phrases that may imply a personal judgement, such as "I'm sorry to tell you that...", "I have bad news for you", etc. Doctors should present patients with a balanced view of the positive and negative aspects to ensure that families are consistently given up-to-date and balanced information about the condition, delivered in a supportive and respectful manner. Doctors should mention that individuals with Down Syndrome can be healthy, but do have some degree of intellectual disability, and sometimes health concerns. Expecting mothers should be provided with an information package that includes resourceful Down Syndrome information and organizations. It is important that doctors explain that it is the expecting parent's choice to continue with the pregnancy and not enforce abortion in any way.

Because I know that there are still countless women experiencing the same negative and insensitive approach from their medical team, I would like to change that with the Choosing Noah Bill.  This bill will make it a legal requirement for all medical staff to give a Down Syndrome diagnosis with a compassionate and neutral approach. This will require them to provide equal proportion of "negative' and "positive" information about the condition. Terminating our pregnancy should not be enforced and we should not have to feel as if we are doing something wrong by keeping our baby. If we choose to continue with our pregnancy, we should not be reminded at every doctor's visit that we can still terminate it or of all the medical conditions and stress that may come with having our child. FUN FACT: The most common musculoskeletal effects of Down syndrome include weak muscle tone (hypotonia) and ligaments that are too loose (ligament laxity). This leads to excessive joint flexibility.

I’ve been getting some hate mail regarding this petition and I want to set the record straight for those who are against it because they are pro-abortion or against Down Syndrome. To be clear, this is not an anti-abortion bill, it is a bill that I created to end the negative approach that some medical practitioners use when giving a Down Syndrome Diagnosis. We want to allow expecting mothers the right to equal amount of negative and positive information (not just the worst-case-scenarios). What they choose to do with that information is up to them and they should not be judged in any way. I pray that this bill gets passed so that other women do not have to experience what I, myself along with countless women did when we were told about our diagnosis. I will not be silenced by fake pages and/or ignorance.

Hypertension is a type of high blood pressure that affects arteries in the lungs and in the heart. Pulmonary hypertension affects arteries in the lungs and the right side of the heart. Noah was diagnosed with Pulmonary Hypertension when he was one month old. It was a scary time for us because he was fighting for every breathe he took. I sat by his crib while he slept, watching his chest go up and down and even found myself breathing deep in and out as if I was trying to breathe for him. I hardly slept and when I did get a little bit of sleep, I was woken up by his breathing machine beeping every time his numbers went down. There were some scary nights, when he would stop breathing and I had to wake him up just so he could breathe. There is usually no cure for hypertension but there are ways to keep your symptoms from getting worse. I try to keep dairy away from Noah’s diet and add more beets, pumpkin and kale. Apples are also great because they have been proven to reduce lung decline and even reduce lung damage. Currently, Noah’s hypertension is considered “stable” or “in remission” and he no longer requires oxygen support for his lungs which we are so thankful for. 🙏🏽💙💛

Medical Update: 
Today Noah visited a dermatologist to confirm what his primary doctor suspected. His dermatologist confirmed that he does have Vitiligo. Vitiligo is an autoimmune disorder that affects the skin’s pigmentation. Noah’s vitiligo began in his buttocks and the discoloration is growing pretty rapid. The doctor said that she can’t predict if it will happen in other areas and what the areas will be. There’s a 3% chance for people with Down Syndrome to have this and more common in African Americans. It’s also more common for Vitiligo and Thyroid disease to coincide. Noah has been frequently screened for Thyroid disease due to his Down Syndrome. Vitiligo is not something I even imagined for Noah but I am thankful that it’s that and not something more serious. I will try to provide more info on this as I educate myself more about it.

I haven’t slept…my baby is fighting a viral infection and has had this rash and fever since yesterday. We’ve been experiencing this reaction off and on since his Neutropenia diagnosis. As of now, his body is able to fight the bacteria but if it becomes chronic, his doctor said a plan will go into place. Neutropenia attacks white blood cells and bone marrow. I’m trying to learn more about it and find ways to help my baby. In the meantime, I am cuddling and keeping him comfortable and hydrated. Please say a little prayer for our superhero 🙏🏽

UPDATES: Hey Super Fam! Noah wanted to say hello and thank you for the prayers. Last night the rash worsened but thankfully it was gone when he woke up this morning. I believe in the power of prayer so thank you so much for praying and sending good energy our way. Right now, the only thing I’m concerned about is his loss of appetite and fever that only goes down but wont go away. I’ve been on video calls with urgent care and his primary doctor and they suggested that I wait until tomorrow to see if the fever stops. If it doesn’t, I have to bring him in for testing. They say it can be strep throat or another type of bacterial infection. For now, I’m trying to get him to eat and keeping him hydrated and comfortable. I’ve been cuddling with him in bed most of the day and watching @babyfirst when he’s not sleeping. Hope this virus goes away soon 🙏🏽💛💙

October is Down Syndrome Awareness Month. I want to take this time to let expecting moms who have recently received a Down Syndrome Diagnosis that I know how difficult it is to receive that news. We hurt, we worry, we wonder about the future of our expecting child and our lives. My advice to those moms is to choose love and to have lots of faith. God doesn’t make mistakes and you have been chosen for a reason. I believe God chose me for Noah for a reason. I might not know all the reasons but I do know that he has changed me for the better. I now have a different kind of strength that I never knew I had. Patience and understanding are some of the other things that have improved in me. Dear expecting mom, just know that there isn’t a website, book, or social media page that can tell you exactly what this journey will be like but I can assure you that the love that comes with this journey will be indescribable 💙💛💙 Despite your fears, choose love! #ChoosingNoah @choosingnoah

Not a good day at the dentist office today, my baby has to have a tooth extracted. It’s something I knew would take place but wasn’t sure how they would handle it. Due to Noah’s medical history, especially his heart condition and sleep apnea, putting him under anesthesia is always a big deal. What is normally done at a dental office, has to be done at the hospital and might require an overnight stay to monitor him after. Children with Down Syndrome tend to have issues with their teeth. People typically use the term “dental problems” to refer to conditions that affect their oral health. Dental problems include cavities, tooth erosion, gum infections, and gum diseases. In Noah’s case, his baby teeth don’t fall out which makes the new tooth grow in the wrong spot.

When I look at Noah now and all of his accomplishments, I along with his older brothers are so proud of him. I’m proud of my courage and thankful that I chose love over statistics. Despite his diagnosis and medical conditions, Noah has always had a love for taking pictures, modeling comes so natural to him. I am happy to see him doing what he loves to do. As I previously mentioned, yesterday was one of those doctor’s appointments that gives me anxiety. Noah had to see one of his favorite and most important doctors, his cardiologist. In our last visit a few months back, Noah’s test results showed that he was close to borderline heart failure. This visit would either show improvements or that his condition has worsened. I always hold my breath during the echo exams. After a few years of good and bad test results, I realized that if an exam takes long, that means something is wrong. Yesterday, the exam was quick and the doctor didn’t come in to finish the echo so I knew it was good news. In the end, Noah’s doctor said that his heart has gotten better, he also mentioned that he can tell by Noah’s skin color and his energy that his heart is not making him as irritable and tired as before. He went on to say that he is amazed at Noah’s improvements and proud of his accomplishments. Like I said before, this was the first doctor to give me hope during my pregnancy. He never made me feel like keeping my baby was a bad decision, instead he said “babies with this heart condition can have a good life because these heart surgeries are now more advanced” If you guys could see the way this man looks at Noah…it’s pure joy and with so much love. There’s no cure for congenital heart disease so Noah will have more heart surgeries in the future. I’m just so thankful that things are good right now and he can enjoy life with a strong stable heart 🙏🏽❤️‍🩹
